  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Provision of Food and NFIs to Survivors in Kaningo - WONES</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">- 150 households will have access to food and blankets; 
- 400 girls and women will have clothing; 
- Community feels consulted and appreciated as they inform at each step of the response.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Our planned response activities prioritise a) relieving hunger through food provision and b) improved protection, dignity and comfort through sanitation kits, clothing and blanket distributions. Christian Aid will conduct a rapid assessment to determine the modality of food access and respond accordingly. Initial discussions with affected households indicated that food distribution, as opposed to cash, was the preferred method of assistance. This was mainly due to initial shock and loss of basic items including clothes. Most of the people we consulted felt embarrassed to travel to the market in the same dirty or torn clothes that they have been wearing since the disaster happened. CA and its partners will combine both cash and in-kind approaches as appropriate.

CA and partners are well established in the target area and familiar with the local context. Since the mudslide our teams have been on the ground gathering data, consulting with locally affected populations and meeting with various officials for input into the best suited activities.</narrative>
  </description>
